    Date: Sat, 4 Oct 86 19:57:33 EDT
    From: Hans-Werner Braun &lt;hwb@MCR.UMICH.EDU&gt;

    Hi:
 
    With one exception (a host supporting the Diamond/X.400 package) I do not have
    WKS records in my domain data base. Is someone verifying in any mailer
    whether there is a TCP/SMTP available prior to exporting mail? I have the
    impression that nobody cares anyway, so I left the WKS records out. I'd be
    happy to change that in my data base if there are implementations around 
    which "do it right".

I don't think I can claim that our (Symbolics) software does everything
completely right, but it cares very much about what services a host
offers, and tries to do the right thing when figuring out how to go
about getting at them.  One reason it doesn't "just assume" is that we
speak a variety of network protocols, and the software looks at what
service/medium/protocol combinations (ie STORE-AND-FORWARD-MAIL service
via TCP/SMTP or via CHAOS/CHAOS-MAIL) are available when proposing to
contact a host, so it can choose the best way for its purposes.  When
our mailer discovers that it's been directed to forward mail to some
host, but some domain server told it that host doesn't offer any
services, including mail, it gets quite upset.  I don't know about the
rest of the world, but things would be easier for us if everyone was
careful to maintain accurate representations of their hosts' advertised
services.

